Introduction¶

Launched since 2005, YouTube has recently become one of the most popular video-sharing platforms across the world. Nowadays, no matter where you are, as long as you have a device that can be connected to the internet, you can have a great time with YouTube.

Behind the great business value of the company, however, the big data created by millions of users are also extremely valuable. Since video watching has become one crucial part of the modern lifestyle, the wacthing habits of people can reflect a lot about how people think and what do they do. Even their culture.

Is there certain category of videos people prefer to see? Do people tend to watch Youtube during weekends or weekdays? Is there a correlation between people's different watching habits and different cultural backgrounds they have? In other words, are there any kinds of videos that are easier to become popular in US as compared to other countries?

In this project, we will take a insight of the cultural differences using trending YouTube video statistics such as views, likes, comments,average trending time of popular videos in Youtube, and tried to reveal people's video-watching preferences based on their locations.

What videos are considered as "trending"?¶

According to Variety Magazine, To determine the years top-trending videos, YouTube uses a combination of factors including measuring users interactions (number of views, shares, comments and likes). Note that theyre not the most-viewed videos overall for the calendar year. The final top 10 trending-videos list is ranked by views.

To show how trending videos are calculated, we took a random sample of 30 trending videos from US dataset and normalized the four statistics (numbers of views, likes, comments and dislikes) to calculate the percentage each number takes for the trendingness calculation.

random.seed(4)
us_sample_index = [random.randint(1,len(US))for i in range(30)]
sample_us = US.loc[us_sample_index]
us_views_sum = sample_us["views"].sum()
us_likes_sum = sample_us["likes"].sum()
us_dislikes_sum = sample_us["dislikes"].sum()
us_comments_sum = sample_us["comment_count"].sum()

sample_us["views_pct"] = sample_us["views"]/us_views_sum * 1000
sample_us["likes_pct"] = sample_us["likes"]/us_likes_sum * 1000
sample_us["dislikes_pct"] = sample_us["dislikes"]/us_dislikes_sum * 1000
sample_us["comment_pct"] = sample_us["comment_count"]/us_comments_sum *1000

sample_us["xviews_pct"] = (sample_us["views"]/us_views_sum * 1000)/(sample_us["views_pct"] +sample_us["likes_pct"] + sample_us["dislikes_pct"] + sample_us["comment_pct"] )
sample_us["xlikes_pct"] = (sample_us["likes"]/us_likes_sum * 1000)/(sample_us["views_pct"] +sample_us["likes_pct"] + sample_us["dislikes_pct"] + sample_us["comment_pct"] )
sample_us["xdislikes_pct"] = (sample_us["dislikes"]/us_dislikes_sum * 1000)/(sample_us["views_pct"] +sample_us["likes_pct"] + sample_us["dislikes_pct"] + sample_us["comment_pct"] )
sample_us["xcomment_pct"] = (sample_us["comment_count"]/us_comments_sum *1000)/(sample_us["views_pct"] +sample_us["likes_pct"] + sample_us["dislikes_pct"] + sample_us["comment_pct"] )

From the heatmap above, we can see that trendingness of videos are not always determined by any single factor but a combination of all four statistics. Data¶

Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasnaek/youtube-new

Collected through YouTube API, the dataset consists lists of top trending videos in YouTube from five countries, including the United States, Great Britain, Germany, Canada, and France during the period from November 14th 2017 to February 18th 2018. In this project, to remain the language consistency and comparability, we will only invesitage the data from United States, Great Britain and Canada.

Each regions data is in a seperate table but with the same measurements. There are 16 columns in total in each table including basic and fundamental information of the videos such as title, chanel_title, trending_date, views and likes as well as dislikes. With up to 200 trending videos per day, each table has around 18900 lines of data.

Methods¶

(1) Data Selection and Dataframe Construction --> Pandas

(2) Plotting --> Tableau/Seaborn/Pyplot

Questions¶

  • Q1: How do people's interests change across countries?
  • Q2: How do people's watching habits change across countries?
  • Q3 : Is social event a significant factor affecting the popularity of videos?

Assumptions¶

Q1: How do people's interests change across countries?¶

(1) Due to the closeness of geographical locations and the similar historical backgrounds, we expect that the United States and Canada would be more related in terms of people's interests.

(2) In terms of topics, we expect that sports, food, music and politics might be the most popular ones in all three countries. Furthermore, American people might be more interested in sports than the other two countries, while British people may prefer music videos more.

Q2: How do people's watching habits change across countries?¶

Due to the worldwide popularity of YouTube, we assume that the average times needed for a video to become trending are similar among the three countries. However, videos that match people's interest (see Q1) may take shorter times.

Q3 : Is social event a significant factor affecting the popularity of videos?¶

We expect that social event should be a crucial factor affecting the popularity of videos. For example, the popularity of videos related to Super Bowl should increase during the weeks before and after the Super Bowl weekend.

Step 1: Data Cleansing¶

The dataset is relatively clean and well organized. However, to do some special calculations, we need to change the data form of several fields.

First, we modified the tag fields to seperate the tags from long strings into lists.

def replace_quo (l):
    newl = []
    for item in l:
        item = item.replace('"', '')
        
        newl.append(item)
    return newl

US["xtags"]= US["tags"].apply(lambda x: x.split("|"))
US["xtags"] = US["xtags"].apply(lambda x: replace_quo(x))

CA["xtags"]= CA["tags"].apply(lambda x: x.split("|"))
CA["xtags"] = CA["xtags"].apply(lambda x: replace_quo(x))

GB["xtags"]= GB["tags"].apply(lambda x: x.split("|"))
GB["xtags"] = GB["xtags"].apply(lambda x: replace_quo(x))

import datetime

def days_between(d1, d2):
    d1 = datetime.strptime(d1, "%Y-%m-%d")
    d2 = datetime.strptime(d2, "%Y-%m-%d")
    return abs((d2 - d1).days)

In [25]:
top_10_channels = [us_top10_channels,ca_top10_channels,gb_top10_channels]

def top10_views_times(country):
    c_top10 = []
    c = all_frames[country]
    c_channels = top_10_channels[country]
    for i in range(10):
        temp = c[c["channel_title"] == c_channels.index[i]].drop_duplicates(subset='video_id', keep="last").sort_values(by=['views'])[0:5]
        c_top10.append(temp)

    l=[]
    for channel in c_top10:
        for i in range(5):
            channel_title = channel['channel_title'].tolist()
            views = channel['views'].tolist()
            date = channel['xtrending_date'].tolist()   
        temp = pd.DataFrame({'Channel':channel_title,'Views':views, 'Date':date})
        l.append(temp)
    
    return pd.concat(l,ignore_index=True)  

us_top10_views = top10_views_times(0)
ca_top10_views = top10_views_times(1)

def views_per_day_correct(l):
    if len(l) <= 1: return l
    res = [0]*len(l)
    res[0] = l[0]
    for i in range(1,len(l)):
        res[i] = l[i] - l[i-1]
        
    return res

def views_per_day(vid,country):
    c = all_frames[country]
    v = c[c['video_id'] == vid]
    v_trend_times = v["views"].tolist()
    v_trend_times_corr = views_per_day_correct(v_trend_times)
    
    return v_trend_times_corr

From the case study, we found that the Red Sparrow Trailer was taking way more time to become popular in the Great Britain (13 days) than in U.S. and Canada (1 day). We think it's probably related to the location, because the movie was first releasd in the states and then to Europe.

However, by scanning the total number of views and likes of the video, we found that, even though it took longer times to become trending, the Trailer is favored the most by British people, as they generally have more responses, such as comments and likes, than the other two countries.

Q3 : Is social event a significant factor affecting the popularity of videos?¶

To answer this question, we created a map of popular words in video titles and selected three most representative words to see the trend variations during the 4 months.

In [36]:
import string
from operator import itemgetter
exclude = set(string.punctuation)

def get_rid_of_punctuations(s):
    result = ""
    for ch in s:
        if ch not in exclude:
            result = result + ch
    return result

def get_word_map(data):
    word_map = dict()
    for each in data["title"]:
        for word in each.split():
            w = get_rid_of_punctuations(word) 
            if w in word_map: word_map[w] = word_map[w] + 1
            else: word_map[w] = 0
    return word_map
        
US_word_map = get_word_map(US)
US_sorted_word_map = sorted(US_word_map.items(), key=itemgetter(1), reverse = True)

CA_word_map = get_word_map(CA)
CA_sorted_word_map = sorted(CA_word_map.items(), key=itemgetter(1), reverse = True)

GB_word_map = get_word_map(GB)
GB_sorted_word_map = sorted(GB_word_map.items(), key=itemgetter(1), reverse = True)

us = [US_sorted_word_map[i][0] for i in range(200)]
ca = [CA_sorted_word_map[j][0] for j in range(200)]
gb = [GB_sorted_word_map[k][0] for k in range(200)]

From the graph above, we can see that the frequency of the word "Bowl" in U.S. suddenly increased durinhg the 13th week, which is the super bowl week.

In Canada, however, the word drama has always been popular throught the year.

In the Great Britain, the number of videos about "Harry" suddenly increased at the 3rd week, when the British songwriter Harry Styles released his new song-Kiwi.

Implication¶

Cultural difference is a crucial factor in Youtubes video trends. Certain categories of videos are easier to become popular in certain countries. Sports-related videos are favored by people in the US and UK, while TV shows and drama are the kind that is popular in Canada throughout the year. Songs of local songwriters, movies and tv series that try to cater local peoples cultural preferences are not that welcome by international audiences.

Despite differences, there are common video trends in Youtube across all countries we analysed. People watch Youtube for fun ! Videos about music, movies, jokes and humor are the most eye-catching and attracting ones for viewers. Also, people look for news feed and commentary of current hitting topics. Channels like CNN and Washington Post consist of a large part of popular channels and videos of Presidents address, reforms, and famous commentators become trending shortly after posts.
